This is a new business downtown Oakley on Main Street. The food and server were very good.  Pay up front, then sit down to eat either outside or inside.  We chose outside and watch the Amtrak train goes by.  They had outside heater to keep warm on a cool day.  Our orders: Chicken kabobs and chopped burger - both are good.  Money worth - Check it out. We will come back again.< /text>

< Review>
Wanted to try something new tonight so we headed out to Oakley Tavern. I had heard only great things from my coworkers. We ordered a few kababs, a wrap, and desserts. Everything was AMAZING. They packed so much flavor into the meat, I couldn't put it down! We shared the desserts, they were all delicious. Im not sure what it was, but it was a almond pudding something, it was delicious. Not only was all of the food flavorful and tasty, but the staff was super nice. They were all friendly, attentive, and had a smile on their face. It was a wonderful experience and we can't wait to go back and support a fantastic local business!< /Review>

<date>1600835548259</date><username>Kute KittyKat Productions< /username><Text>Finally, Oakley has a kebab restaurant!

We decided to try a selection of dishes.

The pizza crust is deliciously chewy and smoky. Itâ€™s the best crust Iâ€™ve had at any local pizza place. The sauce and toppings are presented nicely but are about average in taste and selection.

The chicken wings were juicy but otherwise also average. Itâ€™s nice to get carrots as well as celery with wings, but I wish they were hand cut spears, rather than those kiddie-style baby carrots.

Where Oakley Tavern shines is their kebabs.

We had each kind: Chicken, Beef, and Chapli. These are truly excellent dishes. The meat is well-seasoned and grilled perfectly, with a lovely char. The standout is the Chapli. I donâ€™t ordinarily enjoy grilled mince because it can tend towards dryness. These were astoundingly good - the best Iâ€™ve ever had, anywhere. They were flavorful and very, very tender. This is a dish you could make your name with. Well done!

The rice is a fancy basmati. I believe it might be called the â€˜sellaâ€™ type. The grains are long, plump, have a nice bite, and a naturally buttery flavor. Eating the rice with the meat juices soaking in was pure pleasure.

The Potato-Pea Curry, Green Chutney, and Salata accompaniments were bright and fresh. The Yogurt Sauce was also very good. Whatever yogurt is being used to make this, please donâ€™t change it.

The bread that came with was advertised as naan but it more resembles a thin focaccia. A traditional, chewy, fire-roasted naan would go better. But otherwise, these kebab dishes were flawless.

Theyâ€™re a new restaurant and are experiencing some operational teething pains. It was chaotic, and we only visited on a Tuesday. I canâ€™t imagine weekend dinner rushes there. One of my items was not packed in my to-go order and so I had to go back for it. There was a lot of hectic running back and forth in the restaurant. They have plenty of staff - who are lovely, friendly, and helpful - but there is a lack of organization. An experienced Expediter is needed to orchestrate things to run smoothly and ensure accuracy. And they need to clarify their menu offerings and make it easy for customers to access. A link to their website and a current menu are essential.

Their kebab meals are outstanding. I sincerely hope that they work out these operational kinks because I want very much for them to succeed. (And I hope they add lamb kebabs to their menu soon! Without lamb, it kind of feels like something is missing. Lamb kebabs, please!!)

My family loved this food. Not only was it tasty, it was wholesome and nourishing. Itâ€™s lovely to be able to get takeaway food and feel healthy and well-fed. And on top of it, the meals are a great value. We are so happy to have such a good place to eat locally and we will be back for more!< /Text>< rate>

<UserId.>109530024506240506784< /UserId.>< user_name>
Five Zero Dee< /user_name>
< Date>
1562450896555<//Date>
<rating>4<//rating><Text>I love this park! Most rimes we fo we're the only ones there. The grounds are clean, nicely landscaped and well-kempt. Park is right across the road from railroad tracks and trains do pass by every few minutes so prepare to hear their noise. We've seen folks flying their drones from the parking lot and there are tennis, handball and basketball courts and an 18-hole disc (Frisbee) golf course... something for just about everyone. There's a paw park for your dogs to enjoy and a walking trail of sorts. Allergy sufferers BEWARE and take your Zyrtec, Claritin, Allegra or whatever: there are dandelions and there's so many of them it looks and feels like a pollen alien attack. Picnic tables and little cast iron bbq grills spread about but we haven't used them yet. Best time to enjoy during the summer months is early in the morning or in the evening because it gets HOT right around 11 am and unless you're one of those strange souls who enjoys playing in heat that feels like a crematorium you'll want to govern yourself accordingly. Signs are posted warning of snakes, coyotes and mountain lions but so far we've only seen one coyote... from a distance... on the walking trail... following a lady who was walking her little dog. ðŸ˜²< /Text><pictures>None< /pictures><resp>None< /resp>< Gmap_id>

104665831332264785688< /user_id>
<username>c wong< /username><date>1516417279872<//date>< Rate>
5< /Rate>
< Review>
Probably my favorite Persian restaurant of the numerous Persian restaurants I have tried in California, east coast, and europe...yes seriously they have the best quality meat and best tasting meats! Hands down the best juiciest tender koubideh, shishlik(individual lollipops of rack of lamb nicely charred), gormeh sabzi, fesenjoon, tahdig that is so nice and crisp but doesnt break your teeth when you bite into it, and their special baghali gatogh which are BABY lima beans with a ton of dill and garlic(ask for some lemon wedges to really bring out the flavor), plus when they aren't busy they toast their baklava so the outside is crisp and the inside is juicy hot! Mmmmmm mmmm. Definitely go on a Monday or Tuesday so you have their full attention. Only thing that is lacking is the appetizers and salads compared to the fancier Persian restaurants which instead offer sabzi for free with a variety of herbs instead of just basil. Plus the fancier places would offer jeweled rices. Come here for the best meats and baby lima beans which I have not found anywhere</Review>

Wow this place is yummy! We were greeted at the door by the owner, Sue. She was great, giving recommendations and giving some Persian cultural lessons. I had the special of beef and chicken kabobs with saffron rice. So good! The meat was tender and rich with flavor. My friend had an eggplant dish with a huge bed of saffron rice. Again, delicious and flavorful. The ambience was nice. I highly recommend this restaurant.< /review>

<user_id>101049491497586664785<//user_id><username>C S< /username><date>1440689325344<//date><Rating>5<//Rating>< Text>
This is the second time I have eaten here. Both times it's been outstanding!
My friend asked me to purchase a Groupon and so we went for an early Dinner.

It was spectacular.

Clean establishment, super friendly service and very helpful / informative on deciding what to choose and why without being pushy.
The Baklava is so fresh it just melts in your mouth.
My friend and I are very picky so for us to give a 5 Star rating says a lot.

This second time my Husband and I went for a late Lunch and again just loved everything.
From the warm welcome, cleanliness, to the beautifully prepared food.
Our appetizer the Roasted Eggplant  was so decadent.

We tried the cold and hot Tea and each loved our version of it.
If you go please, take advantage of the knowledgeable host. We thoroughly enjoyed learning details about the carefully hand blended Tea.

Between the Lunch Combo Kabob and my Joojeh Kabob we were in heaven.
The rice was moist / fluffy, and the meat tender / juicy.

I highly recommend  Didar to anyone.<//Text>

<user_name>Christopher Ault</user_name><response>None<//response>< Text>
What a cool church! We went here for a friends wedding. Beautiful and ornate for a church not built in the 1500s, like the cathedrals in rome. The fountain out front is really nice And calming. The presiding bishop(?) Was very nice both at the rehearsal and the ceremony, although he was losing his voice. I'm assuming the wedding planner cane with the church or works there and she was good at organizing everyone and keeping the reverence of the church.< /Text>

117193331479435748339< /userid>
<Name>nonoyo beezewax</Name><date>1567478855536</date>< Rating>
5</Rating>
<Text>I really enjoy this church.  Even if you're not Catholic, it's worth dropping by to see.
The architecture and the landscape are superb.  It's laid out like an Alta California mission with wandering pathways and perfectly chosen horticulture.
I've attended services here and other events such as fish fry's on  Friday's during Lent and every time it's been a thoroughly enjoyable time.
The inside of the church is open, and full of light and has great views of the landscape.
It's simple yet awesome at the same time.
There are very old, quite large, mission bells that are rung for services.
There are fountains both outside and inside the church.
There's also a fun and affordable gift shop.
The staff in the shop are very polite and friendly.
The clergy are welcoming and genuinely nice.
St. Gabriel's did a top notch job making this church the great place it is today, and I recommend seeing it.< /Text>< pics>
None</pics>

< userid>
117330221259898204135</userid>
<username>Victoria Lopez< /username><Time>1562292509730</Time><Rate>5< /Rate>< review>
We had the best time at Madame Tussauds. We were able to park in a parking garage that the website mentioned and there was plenty of parking there. It leads you into multiple floors of shops and clothing stores. The walk from the garage was not very far but it was $17 to park for the day(not a bad deal for the day). We managed to buy tickets online and got a good deal. There's a lot to see and my family really enjoyed it. There is an amazing ball pit on the second floor with beautiful views of the Hollywood strip. It's in the 90s section and you almost miss it if you don't look around the partition that's there, I'm glad we didn't. You can interact with each wax figure when taking pictures as there are props for you to use to make the experience better. We had a great time and would definitely be back< /review>

< review>
What an experience! I highly highly recommend taking the time to visit Madame Tussaudâ€™s in Hollywood! Attached are only a few of the celebrity figures we were able to see while there. They all looked so unbelievably real I had a hard time accepting that they were wax. Definitely purchase your tickets online before going because the prices are better. A VIP ticket (museum, wax hand, 2 souvenir pictures, and a 4D movie) is about $32 online or $60 at the door. It is worth the package deal!<//review>

Totally loved this place! Went right as they opened so pretty much had the place to ourselves. We had plenty of time to take pictures and play around with the props provided without the feeling of "being rushed" by others in line. The staff was helpful and friendly. Definitely recommend!<//Review>

Well this is our 4rth Madame tussauds at Hollywood. We have seen it at Victoria's peak Hongkong, the first ever one at London and the one at Bangkok. As these places have some common celebrities' wax statues but they differ in the sense there are lots of local or area based celebrities' statues more. And also they change their lot periodically. I am proud that we found our Bollywood super star Amitabh Bachchan in every one of them, even in Hollywood one. We like visiting Madame tussauds and taking pictures with wax statues everytime. Also every Madame tussauds has a 4d show which we enjoy. There are souvenir shops at each of them and lots of eateries around it. This one at Hollywood Boulevard was no exception. And this one made sense because there can't be more celebrities anywhere else than in Hollywood. ðŸ‘ðŸ»ðŸ‘ŒðŸ¼ðŸ˜ŽðŸ™‚ðŸ™‚<//text>

<Name>Anthony Bachtiar<//Name><Time>1567617222169<//Time><rate>5< /rate>< text>
Madame Tussauds Hollywood.
This is one of the Madam Tussauds museum built in several places in the world. In this museum there are more statues and represent several prominent figures from Asia.
In addition to seeing a collection of wax figures, you can also see 4 Dimensional film performances at this place.

As  the museum's of entertainment venues, it is well worth a visit and for those of you who like to take photos, there are many choices of characters to choose from.

If you come there with a group tour and while waiting for your friends to return to the gathering point you can entertain yourself by spending  time here. Have fun there at the Hollywood Museum of Madame Tussauds.<//text>

<review>Another of Hollywood's "Must see" attractions. There are a few wax museums along the blvd but I think this one was out favourite.

Set over a number of floors with differant exhibits for decades, films and genres it proves great fun posing with this near realistic figures for selfies.

Buy your ticket before hand and save a fortune on the door fee and don't forget to take a printed ticket. We saw a number of guests struggling to get up emails and scan barcodes from phones etc.

The photographs taken by the team here although a little pricy are great and a souviner worth having.

There is no rush to get around and you are not pressured to move on as you are in one of the other wax mueums in Hollywood. As you get to the end of your tour dont forget to jump in the ballpit overlooking the main road and get some pictures.</review><Resp>{'time': 1618507020666, 'text': 'Wonderful review! Thank you Ruth!'}</Resp></record></dataset><record>

<Text>This place is fantastic! All of the figures look crazy real, sometimes disturbingly real. We went during the week and it was not crowded and they metered entry so there wouldn't be a huge rush of people at once. You can get super close and even touch the figures. This was a lot of fun and I would absolutely recommend visiting!< /Text>< Name>

< user_name>
Cynthia Osiemi< /user_name>
<Time>1529552392692< /Time>< Rate>
5</Rate>
< Review>
The tickets were pricey despite the coupon from the airport. But I think the $38 was worth it. My favorite rooms were the marvel superhero room and the 50s and 60s movie stars. Some of the wax figures bore no likeness to the original stars while some looked eerily like them. It was a fun experience in all. I liked the 3D or was it 4D movie experience as well. Take loads of pictures and buy some relatively cheap souvenirs from the store out front.
You can do without the other attractions I think.</Review>

< Review>
This museum has the best wax statues out of Ripleys and Hollywood Wax Museum. The photographer up front when you first go inside isn't too welcoming but the statues totally makeup for it. Sometimes vendors sell tickets that last like three days that are good for Ripley's, Hollywood Wax Museum, and Madame Tussauds. I would totally recommend getting those if you're intrested in going to all three.<//Review>

<text>Madame Tussaudâ€™s wax museum in Hollywood is a great example of the work started in France all those years ago. <Review>The sole purpose of why I went was to see Selena Quintanillas wax figure. I was completely amazed and in awe of all the other celebrity figures that were in the building. It contains 3 levels of non stop amazing figures the best part is that there's nobody there to interfere with you or the interactions with the people the place is monitored but you have full reign to take up close pictures and to touch the wax figures and have amazing shots some of them even have props that way you can really make your picture come alive and once I did finally see my Queen I was in heaven big shout out to the museum for making such an iconic figure.  They did such a good job on every figure and the place is well kept, clean and neat it's a bit crazy because you keep bumping into the figures that you think that are people and so that was a little freaky but cool at the same time, we were there towards the end of day and they never once rushed us or made us feel like we needed to hurry up and get out so please take your time but don't take to much time. I highly recommend going to see the museum if you're visiting Hollywood definitely worth it and potentially buy your tickets online it'll save you some cash.</Review>< pictures>

< Pics>
None<//Pics>
< review>
Madame Tussauds is an amazing museum. It has so many amazing wax figures of your favorite celebrities. They are so realistic no one would know if it was a wax figure. You can pose with the most popular celebrities. There is almost every celebrity you could imagine. They include every little detail. You can learn a lot about your favorite celebrities. They also have photo stations every once and while. You can purchase these photos after. At the end of the museum there is the option to purchase your photos and see how the wax figures are made. Now the best part is creating your own wax hand. You can customize it with colors and what you make your hand look like. It is just the coolest thing. I recommend going here with the family. It can make great photos to share and wonderful memories.<//review>

<user>113780863220025454333< /user>< user_name>
O Lena<//user_name>
<Date>1499986642069< /Date><rate>5</rate>< Review>
Madame Tussauds Wax Museum Hollywood is located next to Grauman Chinese Theater and Walk of Fame, so it's conveniently located when visiting Hollywood. It is a very fun museum, and the wax figures are so lifelike it's almost creepy: you think they will come alive anytime! I've been to other wax museums before and this one was the best by far! Lots of fun for all ages! You can make fun photos with them, sit with them etc. Also, I liked that it was interactive with different props you can use and put on to really make your pictures that much more fun.
It was definitely worth the money... I would recommend everyone to try it at least once! Visited May 2016<//Review>

<Review>A must visit for anyone visiting in LA. Its a great place to hang out with friends and family as they have personalities from a variety of categories: new actors, old actors, directors, comedians, sports players, super heroes etc. The tickets are cheaper if you buy online. You also get two photos for free. You can also sign up to get a wax hand which is very neat! And if you're a couple, they can do one with both your hands! The people there are very nice! It's a landmark and a great place to take pictures!!< /Review>< date>

< text>
Went to both Tussauds and the Hollywood wax museum down the street. Comparisons:
This one has the better made and more realistic wax figures by miles. Their choice of people leans a little more towards classics, and they have fewer silly props and background sets to take fun photos, but you can really believe that the figures are the real stars, and you can totally check them out in  great detail. They are also a little more expensive, but wow are the figures well made.< /text>

<review>Madame Tussauds Hollywood is a wax museum and tourist attraction located on Hollywood Boulevard in Hollywood, California. It is the ninth location for the Tussauds franchise, which was set up by sculptor Marie Tussaud, and is located just west of the TCL Chinese Theatre (formerly Grauman's). Madame Tussauds is owned and operated by Merlin Entertainments. It features 125 wax figures of famous celebrities - the first ones made for the location were of singer BeyoncÃ© and actor Jamie Foxx. Each wax figure has its own placard placed on a wall in close physical proximity to it, containing information about the portrayed figure. A few matching props have been placed near select figures for visitors to use while taking photos. Marilyn Monroe and Johnny Depp are among some of the figures used in the lobby to entice guests to enter the museum. They also keep things fresh by staying current with new celebrities and movies.<//review><pictures>None</pictures>< gmap_id>

< Text>
We enjoyed the museum. It was smaller than I expected, but it was a good experience for the kids, who had never been to a wax museum. We got a BOGO deal, but it still seemed very expensive for the time we spent there (less than an hour). I would say that it's worth it as a one-time experience, but not if you've visited other similar museums. Especially because of how pricey it is.<//Text>

112854991803380986689<//user>
< Name>
Duky Shepshed< /Name>
< Date>
1562727177790< /Date>
<rating>5</rating>< text>
The Madame Tussauds Wax Museum Hollywood was one of my favorite things our family did while on vacation in Hollywood. The wax figures were extremely real looking, I could fool my friends into thinking I met real stars! Make sure you bring a camera to this attractions, I think I took over 100 pictures here! Each wax figure had their own themed background, plaque with mini biography, props, and some even had props for you to wear in your photo with them. You were allowed to touch the figures, so you could give them a hug or hook arms with them in your photo op. There was a great combination of older and recent celebrities, so it adds an element of education to the experience. Some of the MANY stars my family posed with were Marilyn Monroe, Carrie Underwood, Whoopi Goldberg, Audrey Hepburn, and my personal favorite: Robert Pattinson (I'm a HUGE Twilight Saga fan, so getting to hug "Edward" was a dream come true).</text>

<user_name>Cassandra Yeh<//user_name><time>1531169086176< /time><Response>None< /Response>< pics>
None<//pics>
<review>Weekdays are way less crowded. It only took about few minutes waiting in line to get on the elevator.

3 floors on this location. Started with 3rd floor then follow the route to first floor... ended with 4D show then exit to the gift shop. Great layout! You won't miss anything.

Only 3rd floor has some seating area. Restroom on 3rd floor as well. On 2nd floor, there is a water fountain. On 1st floor, there is hand wax station for purchase.

There are a few photo spots (e.g. Obama, ET, etc), their staffs will take pictures for you. However, those are for purchase only. Pretty pricey too.

Lots of picture opportunity. Bring your selfie stick with you!!</review>< rate>
4<//rate>

<Review>Madame Tussauds has been on my list of things to do in LA for quite some time. Earlier this month I got an opportunity to finally check it out with some friends and had a blast.

The wax museum is huge with multiple levels displaying wax celebrity figures. They put the current famous celebs and then there are the legends. I saw Taylor Swift, George Clooney, One D, Justin Timberlake, Will Smith, Jackie Chan, Obama, Audrey Hepburn and a lot more. All of them were done so well that I had to do a double take! They even had a paparazzi wax figure! A few of us even striked a pose and then realizing it's a wax figure! :D

I recommend it to anyone visiting LA or even if you live in LA you should check it out. So much fun! Don't forget to hit up the hand wax station for a souvenir!

Parking: Hollywood and Highland structure or the lot next to it. They valet for $10</Review><username>Christine Tran< /username><pictures>None<//pictures>< Resp>

<review>I got a groupon deal, essentially 50% off to go, and thought, "why not?"  I'm not really one to visit the tourist traps on Hollywood Blvd, but we were looking for something to do before we met up with friends at the Griffith Observatory, so we bought these. Did not disappoint. There are so many wax figures, and they are all very well maintained and look like their real-life counterparts.  We really enjoyed the action movie/martial arts area (where you'll see a flying Bruce Lee, a Terminator Arnold Schwarzenegger, and a Jackie Chan) and the Marvel area.  The Marvel area REALLY was fun, and included a short 4D movie.
overall, maybe i wouldn't recommend it at retail price, but if you can get a groupon or other 1/2 off coupon, do it.<//review><pictures>None< /pictures><response>None</response>< GmapID>

< user>
102918253898437847981<//user>
< Name>
Rodney S<//Name>
< date>
1445881996919< /date>
<Rate>5< /Rate>< Review>
I got waxed!  And, it was fantastic!

The second Madame Tussauds that I've been to, the other being Vegas, I acted like an attention-loving Kardashian, taking pic after pic with each detailed, well-crafted wax figure.

You can touch them, too!  Some even have nearby props for embellishment.  A few figures don't resemble their real life counterparts much, but most are uncanny doppelgangers.  Multiple floors have celebrities of all sorts - pop icons, sports icons, western, old Hollywood, modern classic, superheroes etc.  Brad Pitt, Marlon Brando, Wolverine, One Direction, Kobe Bryant, Audrey Hepburn, you name it, there's probably a figure there or in the works.  Everyone will find someone they admire.

Besides the wax figures, visitors can enjoy the Marvel Superheroes 4D Experience.  Think "Honey, I Shrunk the Kids" at Disneyland or "Shrek 4D" at Universal Studios.  The short animated film is quite fun, with the best part being the unforeseen "spinal tap" with Doc Ock.

As a souvenir, visitors can pay to have their hands dipped in wax.  Personally, I was content with the multitude pics I took for posterity's sake.

Madame Tussauds has their own valet parking, with another option being at the Hollywood & Highland Center.

Fun times, great memories - if you haven't been to a Madame Tussauds ever in your life, I highly recommend you remedy that situation.  For kids & for those looking to act like kids again, Madame Tussauds is an absolute blast & a great way to entertain the family.< /Review>

114629017963490151120</user_id>
<GmapID>0x80c2bf216e9ca395:0x7608d965074c964<//GmapID>< rate>
4</rate>
<Review>This place is pretty amazing! They have a really large collection of wax figures. Some are on permanent exhibit but I think others are rotated regularly. And different locations have different wax figures, so I definitely want to check out the other locations sometime. They are open every day except for Oscar day, although they might be closed to the public sometimes for private events. They have various passes available for different prices, so check out their website for more info. They do say that buying tickets online is cheaper so that would be recommended. There is an underground parking garage you can use, or if you will be spending time at Hollywood/Highland that is a good parking garage to use as well.

I came here late last year and had so much fun looking and posing with all the different celebrities--who were waxed as either themselves or one of their iconic movie characters. So many photo ops in this place! The wax figures are all placed in different groups throughout the museum. The first section, "A List Party," features the celebrities that are currently really popular. I think this is the section that Ryan Reynolds is supposed to be in, but unfortunately he wasn't on exhibit when I went. The next section, "Spirit of Hollywood," features classic Hollywood icons such as Charlie Chaplin and Audrey Hepburn. "Westerns" is pretty self-explanatory and of course you can find Clint Eastwood here. "Crime" features characters from The Godfather and Scarface, among others. Then you can sit next to Forrest Gump on the bench in the "Modern Classics" section, or sit in the car from Grease with Danny Zuko. "Making Movies" is where the wax figures of famous directors and other Hollywood legends are located. Then we leave the movies for "Pop Icons" where you can find Elton John and Michael Jackson. The next section is "Sports," where a really weird looking Tony Hawk is suspended in the air. (While some of the wax figures are pretty good, others look really odd.) After that we are back in the film industry for "Action Heroes," where I was excited to find Marvel characters. They even have a 4D cinema experience in this section for Marvel Super Heroes. It was fun, but be warned that you get a little wet! The final sectino is "Behind the Scenes" where you can see how they make the wax figures and you can even get your own wax hand.

I had a lot of fun checking this place out and I would recommend it for all Hollywood fans.</Review>< pics>
None< /pics>
< date>
1446945011261< /date>

< user_name>
HR Lee< /user_name>
<Time>1369666712504< /Time><Rate>3</Rate>< Review>
We went online to purchase the fast-tract tickets. It stated that you wouldn't have to wait in line, we could go right in. When we arrived, we saw the fast track star on the carpet. We attempted to use that entrance and were told by employee Jouana, that we had to wait in the line.the line was held up so Jouana could take your picture before entrance. I asked about the Fast-tract entrance. She said it didn't matter, we had to stand in line. We told her we didn't want our picture taken. Again she said it didn't matter, we had to wait in line. I asked for a manager and Sandra "Manager on Duty" for the day came out. I explained the problem and she said they make you stand in line  so we can hear the information about the museum. I told her that I had been to the one in Las Vegas and knew about the rules. You have to stand in line so they can take your picture so they can  attempt to sell you your pictures at the completion of your visit.

While we were waiting for Sandra, I noticed that they had lines out front,  wound like the lines at Disneyland, 5 cashier stands and one cashier. Our visit was on Sunday 5/26. The Sunday of Memorial day weekend. They had one cashier so the line didn't get to long while waiting for Jouana to take the pictures.

It was a very unpleasant experience. Jouana was rude and condescending. She was very unprofessional. I will not return to this location. The front end was inefficient and slow.

The thing they say on their website about the Fast-Track tickets is wrong. You still have to wait in line. I suggest that you spend you money elsewhere. I know I will.<//Review>

<rating>5</rating><Review>(Translated by Google) Marie Grosholtz was a French artist who stood out for her sculptures and busts made in wax, especially of personalities and kings in the 18th century.
In 1835 he founded the first wax museum in London, which he called Marie Tussaud, after her married name.
Due to the quality of his works, and the popularity it achieved, more museums began to open around the world immediately, becoming without a doubt the best wax museums that one can visit.
The realism and the state of the figures, the decoration and theme, the atmosphere, make visiting any Madame Tussaud museum a pleasure and a pleasant and fun time.

(Original)
Marie Grosholtz fue una artista francesa que destacÃ³ por sus esculturas y bustos realizados en cera, sobre todo a personalidades y reyes en el siglo XVIII.
En el aÃ±o 1835 fundÃ³ en Londres el primer museo de cera al que llamÃ³ Marie Tussaud, por su apellido de casada.
Por la calidad de sus obras, y la popularidad que consiguiÃ³, enseguida empezaron a abrirse mÃ¡s museos por todo el mundo, convirtiÃ©ndose sin duda en los mejores museos de cera que uno pueda visitar.
El realismo y el estado de las figuras, la decoraciÃ³n y temÃ¡tica, el ambiente, hacen que visitar cualquier museo Madame Tussaud sea un placer y un rato agradable y divertido.</Review><Pics>None</Pics><response>{'time': 1619718168147, 'text': 'Amazing! <Review>(Translated by Google) Being in front of the entrance of this museum, for the first time, generates cognitive anguish. You do not know one who will look there, even if you have information about their works of art. The surprise is cleared by discovering the real-size figures of actors and actresses distributed in thematic rooms by eras and representative themes. Seeing these iconic representations very realistic overwhelms perception and vision. Identifying each one is a challenge for the encyclopedic competence. However, the most extravagant is to realize the mundane presence of those characters: tall as Howard Hughes, Arnold Schwarzenegger; low as Antonio Banderas, James Dean, Jack Nicholson, short as Jennifer Lawrence and Rachel Welch, the other short and very thin. Other unattractive like Julia Roberts or Lady Gaga, whose attire seems more like a tangle of cobwebs. Still they have their charm and produce belated emotion, since it is not possible to meet these characters in real life. The least interesting, for my taste, are the figures of the fictional heroes of American culture: the spiderman, Captain America, among others. They are heroes full of muscles, inexpressive faces and bright colors very plastic, devoid of humanity.
